# Next.js Page Conventions

## Page Structure

```tsx
import { Suspense } from "react";
import { SomeIcon } from "lucide-react";
import { getData } from "@/lib/feature-server";
import { FeatureList } from "@/components/feature";
import { PageHeader } from "@/components/PageHeader";

function FeatureSkeleton() {
  return (/* loading skeleton matching the real layout */);
}

async function FeatureContent() {
  const { entries, isAdmin, currentUserId } = await getData();
  return <FeatureList initialEntries={entries} initialIsAdmin={isAdmin} currentUserId={currentUserId} />;
}

export default function FeaturePage() {
  return (
    <div className="min-h-screen bg-background">
      <PageHeader
        title="Feature"
        subtitle="Description"
        icon={<SomeIcon className="h-5 w-5 md:h-6 md:w-6" />}
        iconWrapperClassName="flex h-10 w-10 items-center justify-center rounded-xl bg-linear-to-br from-COLOR-500 to-COLOR-600 text-white shadow-lg md:h-12 md:w-12"
      />
      <div className="mx-auto max-w-6xl p-4 md:p-6">
        <Suspense fallback={<FeatureSkeleton />}>
          <FeatureContent />
        </Suspense>
      </div>
    </div>
  );
}
```

## Key Rules
- Wrap page content in `min-h-screen bg-background`
- Always use `PageHeader` for consistency
- Use `Suspense` with a skeleton fallback for server-fetched content
- Content area: `mx-auto max-w-6xl p-4 md:p-6`
- Masonry layouts use CSS columns: `columns-1 gap-4 sm:columns-2 lg:columns-3`
- Server data functions return `{ entries, currentUserId?, isAdmin? }` — pass all to client

